-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Air Mauritius, Athi River, Nigeria Breweries
-- B y   A n a   M o n t e i r o   a n d   J o h n s t o n e   O l e   T u r a n a
-- 2010-11-12T15:55:26Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-12/sub-saharan-african-stocks-air-mauritius-athi-river-nigeria-breweries.html
The  Nigeria Stock Exchange All Share
Index  fell the most since June 7, dropping 2 percent to
25,367.83 by the 1 p.m. close in Lagos, according to data on the
bourse’s website.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index  added 0.7 percent to 84.17 by the 3
p.m. close in Nairobi, paring this week’s decline to 0.2
percent. Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  was little changed at 1,888.19
by 1:30 p.m. close in Port Louis and the  Ghana All Share Index 
retreated 1.7 percent to 6,702.48 by the 1 p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Air Mauritius Ltd.  (AML MP), the Indian Ocean island-
nation’s carrier jumped 1.3 rupees, or 8.3 percent, to 17
rupees, the highest close since November 2008. The company
reported a 73 percent surge in profit for the second quarter
through September to 4.96 million euros ($6.7 million), it said
on the website of the Stock Exchange of Mauritius yesterday.  Athi River Mining Ltd.  (ARML KN), Kenya’s third-biggest
cement maker, gained for the second time in three days, adding 4
shillings, or 2.3 percent, to 175 shillings. Net income
increased 15 percent to 518.7 million shillings ($6.43 million)
in the nine months through September from a year earlier as
revenue advanced 16 percent to 4.39 billion shillings, the
company said in a stock-exchange filing.  Harel Freres Ltd.  (HFRERES MP), which produces 75 percent
of Mauritius’s processed sugar, rose for the first day in three,
adding 0.8 percent to 38.5 rupees. Profit for the third quarter
through September advanced 0.3 percent to 103.4 million rupees
($3.5 million) as sales increased, the Port Louis-based company
said in a statement on the Stock Exchange of Mauritius’s website
today.  Mauritius Union Assurance Co.  (MUA MP), an insurance
company, dropped the most since Oct. 19, retreating 6 rupees, or
3.8 percent, to 153 rupees. The company reported profit of 39.5
million rupees for the third quarter through September compared
with 39.6 million rupees a year earlier.  Nigerian Breweries Plc  (NB NL), the country’s biggest beer
maker, dropped for the first time in nine days, losing 1.7
naira, or 2.1 percent, to 77.8 naira after the company reported
earnings.  Savannah Sugar Estates Co.  (SAVA MP), a Mauritian sugar-
cane grower with interests in property development, climbed the
most in a week, increasing 0.3 rupee, or 0.7 percent, to 46.8
rupees. Profit for the first quarter through September jumped to
82.04 million rupees from 8.833 million rupees a year earlier,
the company said in a statement to the nation’s bourse
yesterday.  United Basalt Products Ltd.  (UBP MP), a Mauritian building
materials producer, advanced 1 rupee, or 0.9 percent, to 116
rupees. Net income in its fiscal first quarter jumped 56 percent
to 76.36 million rupees compared with 48.87 million rupees a
year earlier, the company said in a statement on the Mauritian
exchange’s website yesterday.  To contact the reporters on this story:
